node.text:
“The first clip features a humpback whale rising from the middle of a baitball in absolutely perfect conditions! This whale's name is Snowflake. Snowflake is a very special whale to me as it is the first humpback whale I ever saw breach and the first whale that ever ‘mugged’ me…

“In the whale watching world, ‘mugging’ refers to the moment a whale sticks its head out of the water, making eye contact. Snowflake seemed to recognize our voices. It was a beautiful and life-changing moment.”

“The first clip features a humpback whale rising from the middle of a baitball in absolutely perfect conditions! This whale's name is Snowflake. Snowflake is a very special whale to me as it is the first humpback whale I ever saw breach and the first whale that ever ‘mugged’ me…

“In the whale watching world, ‘mugging’ refers to the moment a whale sticks its head out of the water, making eye contact. Snowflake seemed to recognize our voices. It was a beautiful and life-changing moment.”

Naude Dreyer (@namib_naude) and his friend Antonie rescued this huge seal on February 26. He had a very deeply embedded packing strap that must have caused immense pain. It's really amazing to see him getting rescued. Thanks to @oceanconservationnamibia .

The Polar Bear Family 🐻‍❄️🤍
📹 @daisygilardini: The bond between mother and offspring, and between sibling and sibling, is very strong. It’s the only social structure among normally solitary polar bears to be recognized and identified by scientists. Playing, chasing, wrestling, fighting, cuddling and napping together are all part of daily life for a young bear. The cubs engage in fun and games that prepare them for their roles in life later on. Once weaned the siblings will stick together for a while hunting and playing. Mothers are extremely patient with their cub allowing them to bite, jump and pirouetting all over and around her.
.

.
.
.
